<subsection xml:id="subsec-grouped-quantitative-data">
    <title>Grouped Quantitative Data</title>

    Some data sets (particularly those with continuous data) require several values to be grouped into a single class.  This grouping prevents having too many classes in the frequency distribution, which would make it difficult to detect patterns in the data.  Ideally, the number of classes in a frequency distribution should be between 4 and 20.

    One method for determining the number of classes is the <q><m>2^k\geq n</m> Rule:</q>

    <definition xml:id="def-2k-n-rule">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <em><m>2^k\geq n</m> Rule:</em>
            </p>
            <p>  If we want to decide how many classes to use in a frequency distribution or histogram, we can let
                <tabular>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>k</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                        <cell>number of classes</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>n</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                        <cell>number of data points</cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </p>
            <p>
                The goal is to find the lowest value of <m>k</m> that satisfies the inequality <m>2^k\geq n</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>

<example xml:id="ex-DellHold">
    <p>
        Let's look at the Excel file below and find the number of classes, <m>k</m>, that we should use to create a frequency distribution.
    </p>
    <p>
        <url href="external/sheets/DellHoldTimes.xlsx" />
    </p>
    <answer>
        <p>
            <m>n=50</m>, so we want <m>k</m> so that <m>2^k\geq 50</m>.
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>2^5=32\lt 50</m>, so <m>5</m> is too small
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>2^6=64\geq 50</m>, so <m>k=6</m> is a good choice.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </answer>
</example>

<p>
    Once the number of classes, <m>k</m>, is decided, we must determine the width of each class.  The width is the range of the numbers that are put into each class.  The following formula calculates a good width:
    <me>\boxed{\text{Estimated class width:    } \frac{\text{Maximum}-\text{Minimum}}{k}}</me>
</p>

<exercise>
    <p>
    Let's look back at the file from <xref ref="ex-DellHold"/>.  
    </p>

    <p>
        <url href="external/sheets/DellHoldTimes.xlsx" />
    </p>
    
    <p>
        We found that <m>k=6</m> is a good choice for the number of classes, and let's use that the find a good width to use for each class.
    </p>

    <answer>
        <p>
            Estimated class width:
            <me>\frac{17.4-0.6}{6}=\frac{16.8}{6}=2.8</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            Let's round up to a useful whole number that makes the distribution more readable:  
            <me>\text{Class width}=3</me>
        </p>
    </answer>
</exercise>


